{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493412"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:09:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:09:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1316"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1316","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1316"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.09,0.06,0.76,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1316"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44737"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1316","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1316"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1316"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29611"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"538"},{"type":"tags","id":"4256"},{"type":"tags","id":"4272"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5925"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6218"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42287"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44737","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44737"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-year-old woman is brought into the Emergency Department by ambulance following a house fire in which she was retrieved unconscious. On arrival, her Glasgow Coma Score is 9, pulse rate 130/min, blood pressure 80/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, and temperature 35.0 \u00b0C. She has stridor and does not respond to commands or pain. There are burns to 32 % of her body, including to her face. Her lips are swollen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate immediate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oropharyngeal airway","Aggressive fluid resuscitation","Tracheostomy","Intubation and ventilation","Thermal blanket"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESevere burns affecting \u0026gt;20% total body surface area (TBSA) are considered a \u0022major trauma\u0022 injury. In this particular case, the presence of stridor is sufficient alone to alert to the fact that the airway is at risk of swelling and obstruction. In addition, she is unconscious. She needs \u003Cstrong\u003Eimmediate intubation and ventilation\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf there is any delay, access to the airway with an endotracheal tube might not be possible due to the development of oedema and swelling, resulting in the need for a emergency surgical airway (cricothyroidotomy or\u003Cstrong\u003E tracheostomy) \u003C/strong\u003Eto adequately secure the airway.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOropharyngeal airways\u003C/strong\u003E are useful devices for securing the upper airway, however, in the case of inhaltion injuries there is the concern of inflammation and oedema into the lower airways as well. As such, an oropharyngeal airway may not suffice depending on the extent and severity of the injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluid resuscitation\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Etemperature with a thermal blanket \u003C/strong\u003Eare important components in the management of burns and should be started early however securing the airway is a priority.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Remeber the DRSABCDE approach to all emergency situations - including burns!","Stridor is an indication for immediate intubation in burn victims"],"references":["Burns management guidelines. In: Victorian adult burns service at the Alfred [online]. 2019. Available at: https://www.vicburns.org.au/","Haberal M, Abali AE, Karakayali H. Fluid management in major burn injuries. Indian journal of plastic surgery. 2010;43(S 01):S29-36. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3038406/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29611"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1316"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29611","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29611"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-28T09:11:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-04-28T09:11:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1316"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44737"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationship